WEBVTT

00:01.167 --> 00:03.002
NARRATOR:
<i>Previously on </i>Chesapeake Shores:

00:03.169 --> 00:04.337
You didn't come home.

00:04.504 --> 00:06.881
-You had your life here.
-But all we wanted was you.

00:07.048 --> 00:09.259
It's a miracle
the entire house hasn't collapsed.

00:09.759 --> 00:11.928
-It's pretty much a teardown.
-I can't believe it.

00:12.095 --> 00:13.346
You can't publish this.

00:14.556 --> 00:17.559
-Why?
-It's your truth. Not the family's.

00:17.726 --> 00:20.186
You can't do that with your career.
I won't let you give up.

00:20.353 --> 00:22.564
What if I don't wanna give you up?

00:22.731 --> 00:25.525
It's our Bridge contract.
You don't have operational control.

00:26.067 --> 00:28.987
-You don't wanna do this.
-It's just business.

00:32.407 --> 00:37.662
MAN: ♪ Avoiding certain death
The trucker went across the line ♪

00:38.538 --> 00:44.085
♪ My dad was there to make sure
That I swerved in time ♪♪

00:44.794 --> 00:48.590
You look nervous. Worried
your parents aren't gonna like me?

00:48.757 --> 00:52.469
No. No, I'm nervous
you're not gonna like my family.

00:52.635 --> 00:54.637
My dad can be pretty intimidating.

00:54.804 --> 00:56.598
I'm sure I will survive.

00:56.765 --> 01:00.143
-Used to be a Navy Seal.
-I'm pretty sure I will survive.

01:00.310 --> 01:03.563
If the seafood's from the bay,
you got a fifty-fifty shot.

01:03.730 --> 01:05.273
SARAH: Heh.
-What?

01:05.440 --> 01:07.358
It's a steel-mill case
I've been working on.

01:07.525 --> 01:10.320
I've been finding lots of benzene,
chromium, zinc....

01:10.487 --> 01:13.823
Tied together in an amazing sauce.
You should try it.

01:15.408 --> 01:18.578
-Heh.
-Oh, my God. This food is amazing.

01:18.745 --> 01:21.039
You've definitely ate too much benzene.

01:21.206 --> 01:22.665
Good luck, Bree.

01:25.168 --> 01:27.003
The lucky one is you.

01:27.170 --> 01:29.422
Getting to leave after Mom
and Dad read my manuscript.

01:29.589 --> 01:31.883
-You think it's gonna get worse?
-Take me with you.

01:32.050 --> 01:33.885
KEVIN:
So much worse.

01:36.513 --> 01:39.766
David, I have missed your food
since you closed the B and B.

01:39.933 --> 01:42.644
Come to Sally's, we're taking over
while she visits her sister.

01:42.811 --> 01:46.689
-I thought you hated working at Sally's.
-We get to run it. He gets his own kitchen.

01:46.856 --> 01:49.025
It's just basic diner food,
but it's gonna be fun.

01:49.192 --> 01:50.652
Super fun.

01:50.819 --> 01:52.195
-I'm gonna grab a beer.
-Okay.

01:52.362 --> 01:53.571
[BREE LAUGHS]

01:54.697 --> 01:58.034
Does, um--?
Does he seem bored to you?

01:58.201 --> 01:59.452
No.

01:59.619 --> 02:03.331
I feel like since we lost the inn,
he's itching to keep busy.

02:03.498 --> 02:04.541
So?

02:04.707 --> 02:07.293
So he loves to cook,
he should be cooking.

02:07.460 --> 02:09.295
I can't offer him that anymore.

02:09.462 --> 02:12.924
What if someone else gives him
an offer he can't refuse?

02:13.091 --> 02:15.969
Those offers don't usually revolve
around food.

02:16.136 --> 02:18.346
-I'm asking you to stay out of this.
-How?

02:18.513 --> 02:21.099
You're talking about filing a lawsuit
against my father.

02:21.266 --> 02:22.600
He didn't give me a choice.

02:22.767 --> 02:26.104
Maybe not, but considering everything
that's going on with Bree...

02:26.271 --> 02:28.148
-...and with Sarah leaving--
-So what?

02:28.314 --> 02:30.567
I take a number before I cause drama?

02:30.733 --> 02:34.737
It'd be 20 years before I get heard.
Look, Abby, your dad is wrong.

02:34.904 --> 02:37.323
And before the Bridge gets turned
into a Waffle House--

02:37.490 --> 02:39.951
-It is his club too.
-Oh. He's made me aware.

02:40.118 --> 02:44.038
Maybe it wouldn't be a bad idea
to have a more corporate structure...

02:44.205 --> 02:46.207
-...until you get back.
-Siding with your dad?

02:46.374 --> 02:48.835
No, I'm looking at it
from a business perspective.

02:49.002 --> 02:53.006
Abby, please.
I'm asking you not to get involved.

02:53.172 --> 02:54.883
SARAH:
I'd like to propose a toast.

02:55.049 --> 02:56.467
[♪♪♪]

02:58.386 --> 03:02.390
So they say
that you never truly say goodbye...

03:02.557 --> 03:04.434
...to the people that you love.

03:04.601 --> 03:06.728
So I want you all to know...

03:06.895 --> 03:10.356
...that I mean this from the bottom
of my heart, that this is goodbye.

03:10.523 --> 03:11.858
[ALL LAUGHING]

03:12.025 --> 03:16.738
Seriously, thank you, everyone. Thank
you to Jess and David for the food.

03:17.196 --> 03:19.949
And to Kevin, for everything.

03:22.160 --> 03:24.829
To never saying goodbye. Cheers.

03:24.996 --> 03:26.247
ALL:
Cheers.

03:26.414 --> 03:30.168
JESS:
Whoo-hoo! Aw, we'll miss you, Sarah.

03:31.044 --> 03:32.462
Whoo!

03:40.720 --> 03:43.389
<i>♪ Plane ticket already paid ♪</i>

03:43.598 --> 03:46.226
<i>♪ I'm gone</i>
<i>But it don't mean nothing ♪</i>

03:46.392 --> 03:50.480
<i>♪ I'm close even though I'm far away ♪</i>

03:52.273 --> 03:54.859
<i>♪ That's how I remember you ♪</i>

03:55.068 --> 03:57.695
<i>♪ Stuck here on the red-eye special ♪</i>

03:57.862 --> 04:02.283
<i>♪ I can't wait to see you again ♪</i>

04:03.618 --> 04:07.956
<i>♪ So don't think of me</i>
<i>Not being around ♪</i>

04:09.666 --> 04:15.421
<i>♪ Just listen for the sweet, sweet sound</i>
<i>Of the taxi pulling up the driveway ♪</i>

04:15.588 --> 04:18.591
<i>♪ I'm coming home soon ♪</i>

04:21.719 --> 04:24.639
<i>♪ I'm coming home soon ♪</i>

04:25.098 --> 04:27.392
<i>♪ Da-da, da-da-da ♪</i>

04:27.767 --> 04:30.395
<i>♪ Da-da-da-da ♪</i>

04:30.937 --> 04:33.564
<i>♪ Da-da, da-da-da ♪</i>

04:34.148 --> 04:36.109
<i>♪ Da-da-da ♪</i>

04:36.651 --> 04:39.612
<i>♪ Da-da, da-da-da ♪♪</i>

04:41.572 --> 04:43.324
[♪♪♪]

04:47.704 --> 04:49.497
Wow. What's on the menu?

04:49.914 --> 04:52.959
We've got a walnut-eggplant frittata...

04:53.126 --> 04:56.421
...some arugula-pistachio-pesto
quiches...

04:56.587 --> 04:59.799
...and freshly-baked chocolate eclairs...

04:59.966 --> 05:01.634
-...if you dare.
-Don't do this to me.

05:01.801 --> 05:03.594
That's amazing.

05:03.761 --> 05:05.513
I did not understand half of that.

05:05.680 --> 05:08.516
We are disappointed you won't be
making breakfast anymore.

05:08.683 --> 05:10.768
-You know you don't live here, right?
-Hm.

05:10.935 --> 05:13.271
Connor, I don't think
I've ever seen you make breakfast.

05:13.438 --> 05:16.149
-No. I make cereal.
-Oh, that doesn't count.

05:16.316 --> 05:19.652
-How's it working with Danielle?
-It's, uh, surprisingly easy.

05:19.819 --> 05:21.863
Which is kind of weird.

05:22.030 --> 05:25.450
-I'd think that would be nice.
-It is, but it's, uh, still weird.

05:25.616 --> 05:27.702
KEVIN: Hey, Dad.
-Hey. You're not on the road yet?

05:27.869 --> 05:31.372
No. My fridge is empty, so we figured
we'd grab some food for the road.

05:31.539 --> 05:34.125
Yeah. And we heard David's cooking.

05:34.292 --> 05:36.044
-Where's everyone else?
ABBY: Uh....

05:36.210 --> 05:38.337
Bree didn't come because of, uh, Mom.

05:38.504 --> 05:42.759
Mom didn't come because of Bree.
With Jess and David cooking...

05:42.925 --> 05:45.887
...Gran left early to pick up
some burnt sienna and yellow ocher.

05:46.054 --> 05:48.890
-Burnt sienna?
-Sounds like Gran is painting again.

05:49.057 --> 05:51.350
-How's Trace doing?
-Still upset.

05:51.517 --> 05:53.186
MICK:
I imagine he would be.

05:53.352 --> 05:54.896
[ABBY CLEARS THROAT]

05:58.232 --> 05:59.275
[SIGHS]

05:59.442 --> 06:02.278
-So you're not gonna back down?
-Would you?

06:02.695 --> 06:05.656
Abby, you can't run a business
and not focus on it.

06:05.823 --> 06:10.119
-It gets away from you, you know that.
-Mmm. Yes, unfortunately, I told him that.

06:11.037 --> 06:12.663
I taught you well.

06:12.830 --> 06:14.582
[♪♪♪]

06:14.749 --> 06:16.709
So, what comes next?

06:16.876 --> 06:19.212
It's not for me to say.

06:25.718 --> 06:27.095
[DOOR CLOSES]

06:29.680 --> 06:31.099
Trace.

06:31.974 --> 06:34.435
Hey, Bert. How'd it go?

06:35.436 --> 06:38.147
-Nowhere.
-Mick's attorney didn't respond?

06:38.564 --> 06:42.151
He did. He acknowledged
that the contract you have with Mick...

06:42.318 --> 06:45.446
-...might have weaknesses.
-Great. So, what's next?

06:45.613 --> 06:48.282
You know as well as I do
that contracts aren't worth anything...

06:48.449 --> 06:51.661
-...unless you'll fight for them.
-Okay. Then let's fight.

06:51.828 --> 06:55.832
Trace, I gotta be honest.
If you file suit, it's gonna be costly.

06:56.666 --> 06:58.835
And it might take six to eight months.

06:59.001 --> 07:01.003
So what? I just back away?

07:01.170 --> 07:05.508
It's up to you. Unfortunately, this is
how Mick O'Brien does business.

07:05.675 --> 07:09.387
Yeah, well, maybe so,
but this feels pretty personal to me.

07:12.765 --> 07:14.809
DANIELLE:
Thanks. Okay.

07:14.976 --> 07:18.980
Preliminary tests indicate levels
of heavy metals, benzene, phenol...

07:19.147 --> 07:22.483
...acids, sulfides, sulfates, cyanides,
thiocyanates, thiosulfates--

07:22.650 --> 07:25.361
-Ah, ah. No, no, no. You gotta stop.
-Why?

07:25.528 --> 07:29.198
I had fish for dinner, and now I'm afraid
there's an arm growing out of my head.

07:29.365 --> 07:30.408
You could pull it off.

07:30.867 --> 07:34.203
It's nice when billable hours
include fresh air.

07:34.370 --> 07:35.830
Yeah.

07:37.039 --> 07:39.250
-It is, isn't it?
-Yeah.

07:40.793 --> 07:43.129
[♪♪♪]

07:43.296 --> 07:45.965
You know Jess is only running
Sally's for a week?

07:46.132 --> 07:48.968
I know,
but since Gran wanted fresh flowers...

07:49.135 --> 07:53.347
...I thought that Jess and David would
love some for their first day.

07:53.514 --> 07:56.809
And these are Margarets,
for patience.

07:56.976 --> 07:59.312
Well, she's definitely gonna need
some of that.

08:00.563 --> 08:02.648
Think we all do.

08:03.316 --> 08:04.609
I think we all do.

08:05.401 --> 08:08.905
-There's a lot going on right now.
-You think?

08:09.780 --> 08:13.701
When I first moved back,
your dad asked me why I was doing this.

08:13.868 --> 08:16.245
Was it for me?
Was it for everyone else?

08:16.412 --> 08:20.249
I never answered
because, honestly, I didn't know.

08:23.878 --> 08:27.673
-Oh....
-Well, maybe it was for both.

08:27.840 --> 08:29.050
Maybe.

08:29.217 --> 08:33.012
I guess I was thinking
I could just help everyone heal.

08:33.429 --> 08:37.892
Maybe I was just hoping that by
coming home, we could all just move on.

08:38.059 --> 08:39.685
Oh, I don't know.

08:41.187 --> 08:43.606
And then you read Bree's book.

08:43.773 --> 08:44.857
[SIGHS]

08:45.024 --> 08:48.277
What happened was more complicated
than Bree made it out to be.

08:48.444 --> 08:50.530
I'm guessing Dad feels the same way?

08:51.447 --> 08:54.075
-Has he read it?
-Bree told me she gave it to him.

08:54.242 --> 08:55.326
-Really?
-Mm-hm.

08:56.869 --> 09:00.206
I can't imagine he's gonna be
any happier than I was.

09:00.706 --> 09:03.626
Knowing your dad,
he does not like to rehash the past.

09:03.793 --> 09:05.878
He's all about "tough it out."

09:06.045 --> 09:08.673
Right. Well, that makes two of us.

09:08.839 --> 09:13.386
I was talking to Trace about the club,
and I think I channeled Dad.

09:13.553 --> 09:16.180
Ah, Abby, no.

09:16.347 --> 09:18.558
Don't imagine that went over very well?

09:18.724 --> 09:20.309
No, it didn't.

09:20.476 --> 09:24.105
Hmm. Well, then.

09:25.064 --> 09:27.149
Purple delphiniums.

09:27.316 --> 09:28.359
Forgiveness.

09:28.526 --> 09:30.528
[♪♪♪]

09:32.238 --> 09:35.575
Okay, cleaning supplies are still
in the second closet.

09:35.741 --> 09:39.579
Schedule and receipts are still
under the cash register. Okay.

09:39.745 --> 09:42.039
Can you believe
we both waited tables at Sally's--?

09:42.206 --> 09:44.667
And now we're running the place.
I know.

09:44.834 --> 09:48.421
-And you get to run your own kitchen.
-Yeah, for a few days.

09:48.588 --> 09:52.717
You get to make lunch and dinner.
You get to make recipes without eggs.

09:52.883 --> 09:55.553
That's true.
You're right, it's gonna be fun.

09:55.720 --> 09:59.265
And the best part is,
I get to work with you.

09:59.432 --> 10:03.227
Perfect answer. Okay, get to work.
There's a food delivery box by the door.

10:03.394 --> 10:05.396
[♪♪♪]

10:05.855 --> 10:07.732
-Okay.
-Ahem.

10:09.150 --> 10:11.360
-Uh-oh.
-"Uh-oh," what?

10:11.527 --> 10:14.864
Truffles, saffron, camembert...

10:15.031 --> 10:16.657
...Kobe beef.

10:16.824 --> 10:20.995
This isn't right.
We got a different restaurant's order.

10:21.162 --> 10:22.830
Okay. I'm calling now.

10:24.206 --> 10:25.791
[KEYPAD BEEPING]

10:25.958 --> 10:27.710
Wait, wait, wait.

10:29.378 --> 10:31.714
If they don't want it, I could....

10:32.798 --> 10:35.801
I mean, there are so many things
I could do with this.

10:35.968 --> 10:37.011
Really?

10:56.614 --> 10:58.407
[BOTH CHUCKLING]

11:03.245 --> 11:05.498
You were serious
about growing up on a farm.

11:05.665 --> 11:09.418
Yup. And tomorrow we're up at 4,
milking cows.

11:10.378 --> 11:12.546
Oh. Uh....

11:13.047 --> 11:15.966
-Cool. I guess. Oh.
-Heh. I'm kidding.

11:16.133 --> 11:17.134
WOMAN:
Sarah!

11:18.094 --> 11:19.428
-Oh.
-Hey, Mom.

11:19.595 --> 11:21.514
[BOTH CHUCKLE]

11:22.390 --> 11:24.350
MAN: Hey, pumpkin.
-Hey, Dad.

11:25.101 --> 11:27.228
-This is Kevin.
-Aw.

11:27.395 --> 11:31.732
-It's so nice to finally meet you, Kevin.
-Nice to meet you too, ma'am.

11:31.899 --> 11:34.944
-Laura, please. And this is Wil.
-Hi.

11:35.111 --> 11:38.364
Heard about your offer from N.Y.F.D.
Very impressive.

11:38.864 --> 11:40.449
Thank you, sir. Yeah.

11:40.866 --> 11:43.411
I mean, Wil. Heh-heh.

11:48.833 --> 11:51.627
So your dad likes to shake hands firmly.

11:51.794 --> 11:54.755
Yeah. He does it to test you,
see how you react.

11:54.922 --> 11:56.006
And how'd I do?

11:56.173 --> 11:57.383
-You're doing great.
-Good.

11:57.550 --> 11:59.927
-Because I think he broke two bones.
-Heh.

12:03.222 --> 12:05.433
[♪♪♪]

12:06.183 --> 12:08.978
-Enjoy <i>Pride &amp; Prejudice.</i>
-Thank you.

12:10.187 --> 12:11.981
-I love that book.
-Jane Austen fan?

12:12.148 --> 12:14.275
Oh, a huge one. Heh.

12:14.442 --> 12:18.529
I did my dissertation
on Victorian literature at Oxford.

12:18.696 --> 12:21.740
-I focused on Austen's later works.
-Oxford? Impressive.

12:21.907 --> 12:24.285
-I'm not sure my students think so.
-Heh-heh.

12:24.452 --> 12:26.662
-Where do you teach?
-U-Dub, Seattle.

12:26.829 --> 12:29.665
But I'm in Maryland
to interview at Johns Hopkins.

12:29.832 --> 12:33.836
Which starts tomorrow,
so today I get to do my favorite thing...

12:34.003 --> 12:37.006
-...which is check out small bookstores.
-Hmm.

12:37.173 --> 12:39.216
There aren't many of us left.

12:39.383 --> 12:41.802
Especially ones that do podcasts.

12:41.969 --> 12:45.306
I heard the podcast the bookstore did
with Simon Atwater.

12:45.473 --> 12:46.974
Oh, uh, and me.

12:48.058 --> 12:50.227
-I'm Bree O'Brien.
-You're Bree O'Brien?

12:50.853 --> 12:53.689
I taught your play,
<i>Meditations from the Second Floor...</i>

12:53.856 --> 12:56.233
...in my Modern American Playwright
class last year.

12:56.400 --> 12:59.653
-You what? Wow.
-Yeah. Heh-heh.

12:59.820 --> 13:04.116
It is such a pleasure to meet you.
I am such a huge fan. I'm--

13:04.283 --> 13:05.326
Caroline?

13:05.493 --> 13:06.869
[♪♪♪]

13:07.036 --> 13:08.954
-Simon.
-Simon?

13:10.664 --> 13:13.334
-Caroline?
-Uh, hi, Bree.

13:17.713 --> 13:19.173
[CHUCKLES]

13:21.717 --> 13:23.010
TRACE:
Come here, Axel. You thirsty?

13:25.054 --> 13:26.889
Here you go, boy. Heh-heh.

13:30.935 --> 13:32.478
Hey, Mark.

13:32.978 --> 13:34.396
What are you doing here?

13:34.563 --> 13:37.775
Hope you don't mind me popping by.
Thought you and I could have a talk.

13:37.942 --> 13:39.235
Yeah. Yeah, sure.

13:39.401 --> 13:42.613
-You, uh-- You want a beer?
-Yeah. That'd be great.

13:43.989 --> 13:45.407
Hey, buddy.

13:46.534 --> 13:49.036
Oh, nice place you got here.

13:49.203 --> 13:50.955
Yeah, thanks.

13:51.121 --> 13:53.666
We like it. Heh.

13:54.333 --> 13:56.168
-Here you go.
-Ah.

13:56.335 --> 13:58.337
-Cheers.
-Cheers.

14:01.882 --> 14:04.802
Nice flowers. That your work? Heh.

14:04.969 --> 14:09.265
Heh-heh. You didn't come all this way
to talk about my flowers, did you?

14:09.431 --> 14:12.309
No, I came all this way
to give you some good news.

14:12.476 --> 14:15.688
Knowing you won't
necessarily see it that way.

14:16.146 --> 14:20.109
Donovan's tour has been extended
six more months. Europe and Asia.

14:20.276 --> 14:23.195
With your band getting
a full hour to open the show.

14:23.696 --> 14:24.738
Wow.

14:24.905 --> 14:29.785
Then I got studio time down
in Muscle Shoals to cut a second album.

14:29.952 --> 14:31.954
[♪♪♪]

14:32.580 --> 14:34.707
Sounds like quite a run.

14:35.374 --> 14:38.335
Eight months, give or take.

14:39.753 --> 14:43.215
Heh. Now, ordinarily,
at this point in the conversation...

14:43.382 --> 14:45.968
...people usually thank me
and start packing.

14:48.220 --> 14:51.640
But it's never that simple with you,
is it, Trace?

14:55.352 --> 14:57.897
So you're not gonna try
to convince me to go?

14:58.272 --> 15:00.316
Tell me this is my ticket?

15:00.482 --> 15:03.027
That my life's gonna change forever?

15:03.360 --> 15:05.529
Would it make a difference?

15:06.488 --> 15:08.032
Not really.

15:08.198 --> 15:11.785
Then I'll leave it to you and the band
to figure out what you wanna do.

15:11.952 --> 15:13.412
You got one week.

15:16.248 --> 15:18.417
-Thanks for the beer.
-Yeah.

15:30.679 --> 15:32.681
[♪♪♪]

15:36.602 --> 15:38.020
Your new office?

15:38.187 --> 15:41.565
It was too late to drive into Baltimore,
so I thought I'd work here.

15:43.150 --> 15:44.777
How'd you find me?

15:44.944 --> 15:46.528
Mom spilled the beans.

15:47.071 --> 15:49.615
Ah. Our own Benedict Arnold.

15:49.782 --> 15:53.202
Hm. You know, I could say
the same about you.

15:53.869 --> 15:55.746
I thought
we'd already gone over the club.

15:55.913 --> 15:59.750
I'm not, uh, talking about the club.

16:00.292 --> 16:02.044
I was talking about Bree's book.

16:04.338 --> 16:06.507
I just don't get why she wrote it.

16:06.924 --> 16:09.009
She's trying to understand
what happened.

16:09.426 --> 16:12.721
Well, all she had to do was ask.

16:13.263 --> 16:17.226
Dad, in a family where no one talks,
it's not that easy.

16:17.977 --> 16:22.022
Maybe it shouldn't be talked about. Maybe
what happened should be left behind.

16:22.189 --> 16:26.235
-So we should just tough it out? Hm.
-That's what you and I would do.

16:27.695 --> 16:30.698
But not everyone.

16:30.864 --> 16:33.033
No. Mmm.

16:34.451 --> 16:36.328
LEIGH:
Six months of touring Europe?

16:36.495 --> 16:39.081
And two months' studio time
to record another album.

16:39.248 --> 16:43.335
I know this'll be hard on you with Abby
and taking you away from the club--

16:43.502 --> 16:45.045
Not exactly the best timing.

16:45.504 --> 16:47.715
Okay. French fries three ways.

16:47.881 --> 16:51.343
Plain,
one with caciocavallo podolico cheese...

16:51.510 --> 16:53.345
...and one with a truffle drizzle.

16:53.512 --> 16:55.180
TRACE:
Jess, what are you doing here?

16:55.347 --> 16:57.349
Oh, David and I are
watching Sally's this week.

16:57.516 --> 17:00.477
-Ah.
-And it's perfect because...

17:00.644 --> 17:03.480
...David can finally do what he loves.

17:04.189 --> 17:06.191
-Right?
-Right.

17:06.358 --> 17:09.695
People should always follow
their dreams. No matter what.

17:09.862 --> 17:15.075
Because in the end,
that's all that matters. I think.

17:16.452 --> 17:17.995
Enjoy your fries.

17:18.162 --> 17:19.913
Dude, these fries are awesome.

17:20.080 --> 17:22.249
-Better than Paulie's in Philly for sure.
-Heh.

17:23.167 --> 17:27.963
Trace, I mean, this is seriously
a once-in-a-lifetime opportunity.

17:28.130 --> 17:29.757
Yeah, yeah. I hear you.

17:32.801 --> 17:34.887
[♪♪♪]

17:43.604 --> 17:45.022
MEGAN:
Nell.

17:45.981 --> 17:47.357
This look good to pot here?

17:47.524 --> 17:50.069
Megan, it's beautiful.
The lavender's perfect.

17:50.444 --> 17:52.154
Thank you. Oh....

17:57.910 --> 18:00.245
-Nell, why are you doing this?
-Uh-huh.

18:00.412 --> 18:04.166
Oh, darling, I have always loved painting.

18:04.333 --> 18:06.460
Even when Rome is going up in flames?

18:06.627 --> 18:11.548
Oh, well, unfortunately,
I can't put out this fire.

18:12.716 --> 18:14.551
Only you can do that.

18:15.928 --> 18:17.429
Because I lit the match?

18:17.846 --> 18:20.516
No. No.

18:20.933 --> 18:25.854
Because even a match,
it needs kindling to burn.

18:26.396 --> 18:27.439
But...

18:28.440 --> 18:33.403
...the fire cannot be put out
unless everybody grabs a bucket.

18:36.406 --> 18:37.658
[MEGAN SIGHS]

18:41.620 --> 18:43.080
So....

18:43.664 --> 18:45.707
Caroline remembers you.

18:46.291 --> 18:48.210
-Apparently so.
-Hm.

18:48.377 --> 18:52.339
We were in a lot of the same classes,
same study groups.

18:52.506 --> 18:55.384
We went to the same pubs, places, so....

18:55.551 --> 18:58.387
Sounds like you guys spent
an awful lot of time together.

18:58.554 --> 19:02.474
Well, yes. I mean, it was always
in a sort of group context.

19:02.641 --> 19:06.019
-It was very little one-on-one.
-So you guys never dated?

19:06.186 --> 19:08.564
No. No.

19:08.730 --> 19:12.901
She was always going out
with the president of some club or other.

19:13.068 --> 19:15.988
And although we were often
in the same place...

19:16.155 --> 19:18.240
...her eyes were always elsewhere.

19:18.782 --> 19:20.284
Hmm.

19:21.118 --> 19:27.082
So if the <i>Caroline</i> books are just
a series of "what ifs" and "could bes"...

19:28.417 --> 19:30.919
...why did you call her by her real name?

19:31.086 --> 19:33.088
[♪♪♪]

19:33.714 --> 19:35.966
Because, you know, I....

19:36.842 --> 19:40.304
Well, I didn't think
she knew that I existed.

19:45.893 --> 19:48.478
Well, she knows.

19:49.980 --> 19:51.023
[GRUNTS]

19:51.190 --> 19:54.985
Okay, so, whatever I do,
don't agree to arm wrestle Joe...

19:55.152 --> 19:58.572
...and make sure to compliment Paulie
on his cooking.

19:58.739 --> 20:01.325
-I got it.
-Yeah. That's about it.

20:01.491 --> 20:04.536
If you try to tell me or my dad
that the New York Fire Department...

20:04.703 --> 20:07.831
...is better than Philly's,
you and your two broken fingers...

20:07.998 --> 20:09.333
...will be heading home early.

20:09.499 --> 20:12.211
Ouch. That hurts. Heh.

20:12.377 --> 20:14.171
[♪♪♪]

20:15.464 --> 20:18.342
SARAH: This used to be
my favorite place, growing up.

20:19.092 --> 20:21.386
I haven't been here in four years.

20:21.845 --> 20:23.555
It's beautiful.

20:24.097 --> 20:26.391
Yeah. It is.

20:27.935 --> 20:29.811
I kind of wish it wasn't.

20:32.940 --> 20:34.942
It's where I got married.

20:35.776 --> 20:38.362
Feels like a million years ago...

20:39.696 --> 20:41.281
...and yesterday. I'm sorry.

20:45.869 --> 20:47.746
No, I'm glad you're here with me.

20:49.164 --> 20:50.874
Feels different.

20:52.542 --> 20:53.835
New.

20:57.297 --> 20:58.674
[SARAH SIGHS]

20:59.424 --> 21:01.885
So back to the office
and we'll check these reports...

21:02.052 --> 21:04.972
-...against the ones from the steel mill?
-Yeah. Want some food first?

21:05.138 --> 21:06.765
Yeah, sure. As long as it's not fish.

21:07.391 --> 21:08.558
It's chicken.

21:08.725 --> 21:10.852
Which pollutes the Potomac...

21:11.019 --> 21:13.689
...because processed chicken
creates roxarsone...

21:14.106 --> 21:17.150
...which turns into inorganic arsenic
and flows into the bay.

21:17.317 --> 21:18.694
It's on rye.

21:18.860 --> 21:20.404
Oh. Makes all the difference.

21:21.488 --> 21:23.407
Hey, you know what this reminds me of?

21:23.573 --> 21:25.742
-That diner in Brooklyn.
-Yeah. Yeah, yeah.

21:25.909 --> 21:27.202
Yeah, where we used to study?

21:27.369 --> 21:30.289
-And all the show tunes.
-Oh, right.

21:30.455 --> 21:32.499
I mean,
they did have good chicken sandwiches.

21:32.666 --> 21:35.544
That is true. And incredibly bad music.

21:35.711 --> 21:39.047
-You're not gonna sing, are you?
-Depends how nicely you ask me to stop.

21:39.464 --> 21:41.174
Ah. Heh.

21:42.384 --> 21:43.427
What?

21:44.386 --> 21:46.763
Nothing. Thank you for the sandwich.

21:47.723 --> 21:49.266
You're welcome.

21:49.975 --> 21:51.685
[♪♪♪]

21:58.650 --> 22:02.487
Uh, these are for you.

22:03.280 --> 22:04.573
Uh.... Heh.

22:05.532 --> 22:07.576
I don't think
anyone's bought me flowers before.

22:07.743 --> 22:11.913
Not just flowers, these are delphiniums
for forgiveness.

22:12.080 --> 22:16.251
I talked to my dad, and I just--
I wanted to apologize.

22:16.418 --> 22:19.504
Abby, it's-- It's fine.

22:20.464 --> 22:25.093
In fact, there was something
I wanted to talk to you about.

22:25.802 --> 22:27.345
Me first.

22:27.888 --> 22:29.097
I brought you flowers.

22:29.264 --> 22:32.142
-Is that how this works?
-Yeah. I didn't make the rules.

22:34.061 --> 22:35.103
Um....

22:37.981 --> 22:41.526
I wanted to apologize for suggesting
that you should be okay...

22:41.693 --> 22:43.361
...with my dad running the club.

22:43.528 --> 22:46.239
I get it. Your dad was just looking out
for his interests.

22:46.406 --> 22:49.159
Well, yeah. But it's not just that.
It's also about...

22:49.326 --> 22:52.954
...realizing that the club
isn't just business for you.

22:53.121 --> 22:55.874
It's your heart and your soul.

22:56.041 --> 22:58.877
You shouldn't have to give up
what you love.

22:59.961 --> 23:03.173
And I'm sorry that I lost sight of that...

23:03.673 --> 23:06.384
-...and I didn't defend you.
-Abby, it's okay.

23:08.637 --> 23:10.347
I love you.

23:11.973 --> 23:13.767
I love you too.

23:13.934 --> 23:17.229
And when you're finally home,
the club should be there for you.

23:17.395 --> 23:19.439
[♪♪♪]

23:27.531 --> 23:29.407
CAROLINE: You were the one
that convinced everyone...

23:29.574 --> 23:32.202
...to take a midnight swim
in the Cherwell River.

23:32.369 --> 23:33.912
Yes. Yes.

23:34.079 --> 23:36.790
An all-around ill-advised decision, I think.

23:36.957 --> 23:38.875
You swam in a river at night? You did?

23:39.042 --> 23:40.794
-Yeah.
CAROLINE: We all did.

23:40.961 --> 23:44.214
Ah, we got into so much trouble.

23:44.381 --> 23:47.134
I am-- I'm just shocked. Heh.

23:47.300 --> 23:49.636
Two soda waters with lime.

23:49.803 --> 23:52.806
And one soda water
with two lemon slices.

23:52.973 --> 23:56.643
Chapter 13: "Caroline loved soda water
with lemon slices."

23:56.810 --> 23:59.104
-I'm a big fan of the books.
CAROLINE: Thanks.

23:59.271 --> 24:01.731
I can't believe you're real,
that you're here.

24:01.898 --> 24:06.153
Not that you shouldn't be. Well....
I'll go get your food.

24:07.028 --> 24:08.071
[CAROLINE CHUCKLES]

24:08.238 --> 24:12.284
So, Caroline,
I thought you didn't remember Simon?

24:12.450 --> 24:16.913
I actually did, but when Simon came
to find me in Washington...

24:17.330 --> 24:21.501
...I was in a relationship, and I didn't want
to make it awkward for you.

24:21.668 --> 24:23.211
So I....

24:23.378 --> 24:26.006
That's when he started writing
about who we were.

24:26.173 --> 24:29.801
Caroline, you do realize
that you're not actually my Caroline?

24:29.968 --> 24:33.805
Who is more an archetype
of many possible Carolines.

24:33.972 --> 24:36.349
And yet you got
the two lemon slices right.

24:36.766 --> 24:38.310
Hardly definitive proof.

24:38.476 --> 24:39.519
[CELL PHONE BUZZES]

24:39.686 --> 24:43.440
You know what, I'm so sorry.
I have to check in on my next interview.

24:43.982 --> 24:45.609
-Thank you.
-Yeah.

24:47.319 --> 24:48.486
Bye.

24:50.155 --> 24:52.324
So, um....

24:52.490 --> 24:55.285
Still nothing from your parents
about the book?

24:55.452 --> 24:57.078
-Nope.
-Oh.

24:57.245 --> 24:59.206
It's like I don't even exist.

25:02.792 --> 25:04.294
It's weird, you know?

25:05.712 --> 25:08.715
My family is so able to talk
about everything and anything...

25:08.882 --> 25:13.678
-...except what really matters.
-Well, you know, maybe it's for the best.

25:15.055 --> 25:18.892
Sometimes a book can spark
a real conversation.

25:19.059 --> 25:22.938
Sometimes you need a bit of fiction
to make things real.

25:23.104 --> 25:24.147
Interesting.

25:24.814 --> 25:27.025
You know what else is interesting?

25:27.192 --> 25:30.904
We talk a lot, you and I...

25:31.071 --> 25:34.157
...but with Caroline,
it seemed like you did a lot.

25:34.449 --> 25:37.452
-Well, it was a long time ago.
-Wasn't that long ago.

25:37.953 --> 25:40.664
I mean, I don't know,
is there a chance that...

25:40.830 --> 25:44.042
...that Simon is still here, just trapped
inside the pages of his book?

25:45.001 --> 25:49.464
Still hoping to romance Caroline?

25:50.382 --> 25:52.384
[♪♪♪]

25:53.176 --> 25:54.219
Bree.

25:56.471 --> 25:58.473
[LAUGHING]

26:00.100 --> 26:03.144
PAULIE: What do you think?
KEVIN: It's delicious, thanks.

26:03.311 --> 26:04.729
SARAH:
Paulie's diner is...

26:04.896 --> 26:07.190
...considered one of the best diners
in the state.

26:07.357 --> 26:09.609
Better than your mac and cheese
and meatballs?

26:09.776 --> 26:11.236
[LAUGHING]

26:11.987 --> 26:15.448
Okay, those were a huge hit
at the Aberdeen Proving Grounds.

26:15.615 --> 26:17.158
Were they?

26:17.325 --> 26:20.203
Okay, they hated it too.
I can't believe you told them.

26:20.370 --> 26:22.664
-I might've let it slip.
JOE: We know about everything.

26:22.831 --> 26:25.333
Even the eggplant,
and how you asked her out.

26:27.377 --> 26:28.878
No, she asked me out.

26:29.671 --> 26:32.048
-Kevin.
-No, I was down at the beach...

26:32.215 --> 26:34.384
...with my sister
and we had just started a fire.

26:34.551 --> 26:35.635
Illegally.

26:35.802 --> 26:40.432
Yes, illegally. We had just started a fire
and who is to show up but Sarah...

26:40.598 --> 26:42.267
...to give me a ticket...

26:42.434 --> 26:44.102
...and her number written on the back.

26:44.269 --> 26:46.771
BOTH: Ooh!
SARAH: I only put it there to help.

26:46.938 --> 26:48.273
-Right.
-Sure, yeah.

26:48.440 --> 26:50.358
-Come on.
-Okay, fine.

26:50.525 --> 26:52.235
-Yeah, I asked you out.
-Yeah.

26:52.402 --> 26:54.154
[ALL LAUGHING]

26:59.784 --> 27:02.037
And we get to tour Amsterdam.

27:02.203 --> 27:06.124
I know you have a million reasons
why you think you should say no--

27:06.291 --> 27:08.251
Actually, just one.

27:08.418 --> 27:10.503
I have a million reasons
why you should say yes.

27:10.670 --> 27:13.006
Okay, Paris, Budapest, Prague.

27:13.173 --> 27:15.425
I mean, Trace,
we get to play the Paradiso.

27:15.592 --> 27:18.720
I heard the acoustics are unreal.

27:18.887 --> 27:20.263
I get it.

27:20.430 --> 27:24.017
I don't think you do. This is something
we've been talking about since Nashville.

27:24.184 --> 27:25.685
Before the band. Just you and me...

27:25.852 --> 27:28.271
-...dreaming of something like this.
-Leigh.

27:29.189 --> 27:30.690
I called Mark.

27:31.483 --> 27:32.817
Okay?

27:32.984 --> 27:36.279
And I wanted to make sure
that you guys would be okay.

27:36.946 --> 27:39.657
He said, no matter what,
he'd have a spot for you and the band...

27:39.824 --> 27:42.994
-...on Donovan's tour.
-So you're just gonna walk away?

27:44.245 --> 27:49.250
-Look, I'm not gonna stop playing music.
-I get it, you can play music anywhere.

27:49.709 --> 27:51.878
But what we have...

27:52.045 --> 27:54.464
...you and me, our band...

27:55.006 --> 27:57.467
...you're never gonna find that again.

27:57.634 --> 28:00.220
Trust me, I know that.

28:00.387 --> 28:01.596
I don't know.

28:01.763 --> 28:03.848
It sounds like you might've forgotten.

28:04.015 --> 28:06.017
[♪♪♪]

28:13.900 --> 28:16.945
Do you ever think about
where we're gonna be in 10 years?

28:18.988 --> 28:21.408
DAVID:
Uh, I don't know.

28:21.908 --> 28:24.869
I'm just trying to figure out
what we should serve tomorrow.

28:25.036 --> 28:26.579
Lobster quiche.

28:26.746 --> 28:28.748
[CHUCKLING]

28:29.666 --> 28:31.459
I like that.

28:31.626 --> 28:33.837
-Thank you.
-Welcome.

28:37.048 --> 28:39.175
In 10 years...

28:40.051 --> 28:42.595
...if every day was just like today...

28:44.097 --> 28:46.182
...I wouldn't complain.

28:47.392 --> 28:49.728
Because I get to be with you.

28:50.228 --> 28:51.354
Me too.

28:54.649 --> 28:57.277
But I'm still scared, David.

28:57.652 --> 29:01.156
Without the inn, I don't know who I am.

29:01.823 --> 29:04.284
It was the one thing I had
that we could share.

29:04.784 --> 29:10.749
So without it, I'm not sure
that you or your truffles...

29:10.915 --> 29:13.668
...or your Camembert needs me.

29:15.462 --> 29:17.297
Every day, I just keep...

29:17.464 --> 29:19.758
...waiting for you to figure that out.

29:25.764 --> 29:27.891
Ratatouille. Ahem.

29:28.057 --> 29:30.602
-What?
-Ratatouille.

29:31.978 --> 29:33.855
We should serve ratatouille tomorrow.

29:35.315 --> 29:37.525
-Good idea.
-Mm.

29:44.908 --> 29:46.910
[STRUMMING]

29:51.122 --> 29:54.042
I always thought
we had something special, Trace.

29:54.417 --> 29:58.463
With your voice, Leigh's hair, my face.

29:58.630 --> 30:02.133
-Heh-heh.
-John, just stick to playing bass.

30:03.009 --> 30:04.135
All joking aside...

30:05.261 --> 30:07.472
...I just don't understand.

30:07.639 --> 30:11.726
You can't buy our sound.
What we have is special.

30:11.893 --> 30:16.356
And that's why I went with you.
And you don't just walk away.

30:22.028 --> 30:23.655
[STRUMMING]

30:28.827 --> 30:32.956
♪ They love to tell us
We'll never make it ♪

30:33.456 --> 30:38.211
ALL: ♪ They're throwing stones
Against the glass just to break it ♪

30:38.628 --> 30:41.089
♪ But they don't live here ♪

30:41.256 --> 30:44.634
♪ They don't know this kind of love ♪

30:45.844 --> 30:50.765
♪ We're not afraid to go the distance ♪

30:50.932 --> 30:55.854
♪ We'll never take that worn out path
Of least resistance ♪

30:56.020 --> 30:57.480
♪ We got it in us ♪

30:58.606 --> 31:02.193
♪ And there's more
Where that came from ♪♪

31:08.491 --> 31:10.493
[♪♪♪]

31:29.137 --> 31:30.638
We're not saying goodbye.

31:30.805 --> 31:35.018
I know that, I just....
I don't wanna leave here.

31:36.394 --> 31:37.645
You.

31:38.479 --> 31:41.858
Kevin, may I talk to you for a moment?

31:48.114 --> 31:51.159
Just wanted to wish you
a safe drive back to Maryland.

31:51.326 --> 31:54.162
-Well, thank you, sir. Wil.
-Ah.

31:54.662 --> 31:56.080
Yeah.

31:56.247 --> 31:58.249
You know, um...

31:59.334 --> 32:02.253
...the hardest thing
about being a parent...

32:02.420 --> 32:04.464
...is seeing your children unhappy...

32:04.631 --> 32:07.133
...and knowing
there's nothing you can do about it.

32:07.300 --> 32:09.594
And, uh, ahem...

32:09.761 --> 32:13.598
...while we don't know
one another that well...

32:13.765 --> 32:15.683
...seeing Sarah with you....

32:15.850 --> 32:17.769
[♪♪♪]

32:17.936 --> 32:19.270
[CLEARS THROAT]

32:20.480 --> 32:22.690
Thanks for bringing her back.

32:27.570 --> 32:31.741
The truth is, she did the same for me.

32:32.951 --> 32:34.285
Yeah.

32:36.037 --> 32:37.246
[KEVIN GRUNTS]

32:37.413 --> 32:41.209
-Got a heck of a handshake there.
-Just trying to keep up with you.

32:41.834 --> 32:43.419
[GROANS]

32:47.966 --> 32:49.175
So?

32:49.342 --> 32:52.804
Your dad cracked my C6 vertebra
and I think he broke my thumb.

32:52.971 --> 32:54.263
[SARAH CHUCKLES]

33:04.482 --> 33:05.858
[SIGHS]

33:06.025 --> 33:08.486
Hey. Shouldn't we be at the office?

33:09.028 --> 33:11.280
We have a series of briefs
due in two weeks.

33:11.447 --> 33:16.869
Yeah. I was thinking we could check
some of the data here first.

33:17.328 --> 33:19.038
Oh. Sure.

33:19.205 --> 33:21.958
Nothing like hanging out
in a carcinogenic minefield...

33:22.125 --> 33:24.293
...for fun and billable hours.

33:24.919 --> 33:26.671
[♪♪♪]

33:26.838 --> 33:28.297
Connor.

33:29.340 --> 33:31.884
Uh.... Yeah?

33:35.263 --> 33:37.306
I'm.... I'm really sorry.

33:39.392 --> 33:42.812
-That wasn't fair.
-No, Danielle, hey. It's....

33:42.979 --> 33:45.898
-It's okay.
-No, it's not.

33:47.150 --> 33:48.693
Because I've...

33:50.278 --> 33:52.905
...also been thinking....

33:54.490 --> 33:56.617
Wondering if, um...

33:56.784 --> 34:00.246
...maybe you wanted to spend
some time together...

34:01.039 --> 34:02.874
...off the clock. Like, uh...

34:07.253 --> 34:09.005
...pro bono?

34:09.964 --> 34:11.758
Something like that.

34:12.383 --> 34:16.137
But I couldn't impress you
with my ability to say...

34:16.304 --> 34:19.265
...aliphatic hydrocarbons
and chloride with complete authority.

34:19.432 --> 34:22.060
-Well, as impressive as that is....
-Heh.

34:40.995 --> 34:42.622
We're definitely off the clock.

34:42.789 --> 34:44.040
[CHUCKLING]

34:51.130 --> 34:53.174
JESS:
It's the silence that kills me.

34:53.341 --> 34:56.928
No yelling, no screaming, just quiet.

34:57.095 --> 34:59.889
It's like we traveled back in time
to when Mom left.

35:00.056 --> 35:02.183
That was the worst.

35:03.351 --> 35:06.813
We need to unplug the volcano.

35:06.979 --> 35:10.483
Or crack the thin ice that masks
the turbulent waters underneath.

35:10.942 --> 35:14.821
Oh, that's really good.
You should write that down.

35:14.987 --> 35:16.656
Not to mention, it's a good idea.

35:16.823 --> 35:18.366
Or a really bad one.

35:19.033 --> 35:20.701
Or a really bad one.

35:22.161 --> 35:25.414
-What? I'm undecided.
-Heh.

35:26.332 --> 35:28.167
-Bree.
-Yeah? Caroline.

35:28.334 --> 35:31.212
Hi. Uh, what are you still doing here?

35:31.379 --> 35:33.965
Oh. I forgot to get it signed by the author.

35:34.132 --> 35:38.344
Oh. You could always wait for
the next one. I hear it might be his last.

35:38.511 --> 35:40.888
CAROLINE:
Yeah, <i>Rest in Peace, Caroline.</i>

35:41.055 --> 35:43.182
Ha-ha-ha. I've heard that joke.

35:43.349 --> 35:45.059
-Me too.
-I do wanna apologize.

35:45.226 --> 35:48.187
When I heard that podcast,
I could hear in Simon's voice...

35:48.354 --> 35:49.981
...that he was over everything...

35:50.148 --> 35:53.067
...so I figured it would be okay
to talk about the past.

35:53.234 --> 35:56.195
I'm glad you got to chat
before you go back to Washington.

35:56.821 --> 36:00.324
Actually, Johns Hopkins wants
to observe my teaching...

36:00.491 --> 36:02.910
...so I'm gonna be in Baltimore
for another week.

36:03.578 --> 36:07.456
If it's okay with you,
I would love to talk about your play.

36:07.623 --> 36:09.917
I'm dying to know about the ending.

36:10.376 --> 36:12.253
Oh, yeah, I would love that.

36:12.420 --> 36:13.462
CAROLINE:
Great.

36:13.838 --> 36:17.008
Okay, well, ha-ha,
it was good to see you.

36:17.175 --> 36:19.177
Okay. I'll see you soon, Caroline.

36:19.343 --> 36:21.470
Okay, bye.

36:22.180 --> 36:24.473
[♪♪♪]

36:25.183 --> 36:27.393
<i>See You Soon, Caroline</i>
also sounds like a good title.

36:27.560 --> 36:29.812
-Of course it does.
-Oh!

36:29.979 --> 36:32.356
[BAND PLAYING COUNTRY MUSIC]

36:34.901 --> 36:35.943
Mick.

36:40.072 --> 36:42.283
I know, you don't like the band.

36:42.450 --> 36:44.452
I have nothing against the band.

36:44.619 --> 36:48.623
I have everything against their music.
And their name. Country Jukebox?

36:49.165 --> 36:50.208
[CHUCKLES]

36:50.374 --> 36:52.084
Okay, I don't like the band.

36:52.251 --> 36:53.711
Listen...

36:53.878 --> 36:56.714
...you went to your attorney,
and he came to mine.

36:56.881 --> 37:01.636
So unless you're gonna file a lawsuit,
there's nothing more to talk about.

37:01.802 --> 37:05.014
I gotta prep business meetings
for next week, so we'll have to--

37:05.181 --> 37:08.226
Mick, I didn't come here
to fight about the club.

37:08.935 --> 37:12.855
I actually came to tell you
that I'm not gonna contest our contract.

37:13.689 --> 37:14.899
I'm surprised.

37:16.025 --> 37:17.818
Yeah, so am I.

37:18.945 --> 37:20.696
What changed?

37:20.863 --> 37:24.825
Tour got extended for a while.

37:24.992 --> 37:26.452
That's it?

37:26.869 --> 37:30.373
You said this was your heart and soul.
Now you're just gonna walk away?

37:30.539 --> 37:32.541
You know it's not that simple.

37:33.167 --> 37:34.210
Does Abby know? Not yet.

37:38.589 --> 37:40.800
I'm gonna give you some advice.

37:41.175 --> 37:43.886
If you really care about something...

37:44.387 --> 37:46.430
...you don't walk away from it.

37:47.306 --> 37:49.308
[♪♪♪]

37:57.608 --> 37:59.735
[♪♪♪]

37:59.902 --> 38:01.696
I think a tasting menu is a great idea.

38:01.862 --> 38:04.156
What about "Moonlight at Sally's"?

38:04.323 --> 38:06.075
We light the whole place with candles.

38:06.242 --> 38:08.286
Wouldn't that be
"Candlelight at Sally's"?

38:08.452 --> 38:11.372
Yeah, but "moonlight" is
so much more romantic.

38:11.539 --> 38:16.210
You've got "Moonlight Serenade,"
"Moonlight Becomes You."

38:16.377 --> 38:18.129
Jess, you okay?

38:18.587 --> 38:21.549
-You seem even more you than you.
-What?

38:21.716 --> 38:23.884
Yes. I'm totally fine. Are you good?

38:24.510 --> 38:25.678
Jess.

38:27.388 --> 38:30.099
Okay. I'm scared.

38:30.266 --> 38:33.561
I don't know
what's happening with us, or you.

38:33.728 --> 38:35.396
-Or us.
-Why?

38:35.938 --> 38:37.565
Jess, we're great.

38:37.732 --> 38:38.816
Yeah, for now.

38:38.983 --> 38:40.151
Today. But I--

38:40.318 --> 38:42.403
What about tomorrow or the next day?

38:42.570 --> 38:45.072
Don't think about the future.

38:45.239 --> 38:46.282
Really?

38:46.449 --> 38:49.285
Termites ate my last future.

38:50.953 --> 38:53.122
Then we'll make a new future.

38:54.623 --> 38:56.042
For us?

38:56.208 --> 38:57.668
Or you?

39:02.506 --> 39:04.884
[DOOR OPENS AND CLOSES]

39:14.727 --> 39:18.564
Thank you. I still can't believe
we live in a place so beautiful.

39:18.731 --> 39:20.316
TRACE [SIGHING]:
Yeah.

39:21.942 --> 39:23.194
[ABBY SIGHS]

39:23.361 --> 39:26.530
It's nice to take a break
from the O'Brien family saga.

39:26.697 --> 39:29.575
With Bree's book and my parents...

39:30.284 --> 39:34.205
...I think everything is ready to explode
and I am in the middle.

39:36.123 --> 39:38.793
-That's where you've always been.
-Heh.

39:40.336 --> 39:42.004
With everyone.

39:42.171 --> 39:47.426
Yeah, except this time,
I might have called a family meeting.

39:49.095 --> 39:53.432
TRACE: Wow.
All the O'Briens in one room, talking?

39:53.599 --> 39:54.725
[LAUGHS]

39:54.892 --> 39:57.478
-You sure that's a good idea?
-No.

39:57.645 --> 39:59.980
No, but it would be a first.

40:04.610 --> 40:06.070
Abby, um...

40:07.363 --> 40:10.658
...we were offered a tour extension.

40:11.492 --> 40:12.743
Six months in Europe.

40:12.910 --> 40:14.912
[♪♪♪] Okay, so...

40:21.127 --> 40:22.503
...you would be gone again.

40:24.088 --> 40:25.423
Well....

40:27.508 --> 40:29.260
Are you gonna do it?

40:31.178 --> 40:32.430
I don't know.

40:48.362 --> 40:50.406
-Oh, hey.
-Where's Dad?

40:50.573 --> 40:52.575
I don't know. I was looking for him too. How'd it go in Philly?

40:57.621 --> 40:59.874
Oh. Wanna have a drink?

41:05.421 --> 41:07.673
So does Dad always have
spare beers onboard?

41:08.215 --> 41:09.467
Yeah.

41:09.842 --> 41:12.636
He once told me
that a good captain always makes sure...

41:12.803 --> 41:17.099
...there are ample rations in case
he has to pick up shipwrecked sailors.

41:17.266 --> 41:20.227
-So I guess that makes us lost at sea?
-Something like that.

41:22.313 --> 41:24.356
So, uh, Danielle and I...

41:24.523 --> 41:26.484
...might've got back together.

41:26.650 --> 41:28.194
Might've?

41:28.360 --> 41:30.362
Okay, we did. Heh.

41:31.113 --> 41:32.573
Huh.

41:32.740 --> 41:35.201
-We're just taking it slow.
-Mm, mm.

41:35.367 --> 41:36.535
[BOTH CHUCKLE]

41:38.329 --> 41:40.539
Gonna tell me what's in the envelope?

41:41.207 --> 41:43.250
Uh, it's an offer of employment...

41:43.417 --> 41:45.878
...to the Chesapeake Shores
Fire Department.

41:46.045 --> 41:48.297
As a paramedic.

41:50.508 --> 41:51.675
Congratulations.

41:51.842 --> 41:54.094
And Sarah just signed up with Philly.

41:54.261 --> 41:55.304
[SIGHS]

41:58.432 --> 41:59.975
To being lost at sea.

42:02.228 --> 42:05.731
If you start singing the <i>Titanic</i>
theme song, I'm tossing you overboard.

42:05.898 --> 42:07.399
[CONNOR CHUCKLES]

42:11.862 --> 42:14.448
BREE: Fine, the book has
everything to do with us.

42:15.157 --> 42:18.786
And maybe it's not who we are today...

42:18.953 --> 42:22.248
...but it is what happened.

42:22.414 --> 42:24.833
Okay? At least from what I remember.

42:25.000 --> 42:28.295
And what happened can't be undone,
but we can take responsibility for it.

42:28.462 --> 42:31.590
And for me, that means not hiding
behind my book anymore...

42:31.757 --> 42:35.553
...and not waiting for somebody
to bless it so that I can publish it.

42:35.719 --> 42:38.597
I'm going to publish it, it's the truth.

42:39.765 --> 42:40.933
It's my truth.

42:41.100 --> 42:42.601
There's a lot you don't know.

42:43.018 --> 42:44.395
I know. We've been through it.

42:45.104 --> 42:47.439
I still don't know anything.

42:48.399 --> 42:49.775
Jess.

42:50.609 --> 42:53.070
I wasn't well, so I left to get help.

42:54.071 --> 42:55.155
But, honey...

42:55.322 --> 42:59.034
...I tried to take you, and you,
and all of you with me.

42:59.201 --> 43:01.870
Megan, you left. It didn't give you
the right to take the kids.

43:02.037 --> 43:04.039
Not to mention
it would've been illegal.

43:04.206 --> 43:06.166
She was trying
to keep the family together.

43:06.333 --> 43:09.253
-By leaving us?
-Okay, we're all here now.

43:09.420 --> 43:11.714
Yeah. Held together by Band-Aids.

43:13.007 --> 43:14.174
MEGAN:
Guys.

43:14.675 --> 43:16.635
I came home to heal us.

43:16.802 --> 43:19.555
Yeah, we wouldn't need
to be healed if you didn't leave.

43:19.722 --> 43:21.640
You know what, Connor, no offense...

43:21.807 --> 43:24.560
...but you don't remember
how things were in the house.

43:24.727 --> 43:25.978
"No offense"?

43:26.145 --> 43:28.355
I remember. I was a kid.

43:28.522 --> 43:31.191
The only people that could explain it left.
That includes you.

43:31.358 --> 43:34.403
-Connor, I was drowning.
-What...?

43:35.195 --> 43:37.489
-I had no choice.
-So you just walked out?

43:37.656 --> 43:39.033
It's not always that simple.

43:39.199 --> 43:41.452
And it was hard for all of us.

43:41.619 --> 43:43.912
CONNOR: Oh, is that right?
-We were 6 and 8 years old.

43:44.079 --> 43:47.041
-I tried to get you to stay.
-I couldn't stay the way it was.

43:47.207 --> 43:49.793
I needed you, Mick,
and you weren't there.

43:49.960 --> 43:53.464
-And you didn't care how I felt.
-Yes, I did care. I did care.

43:53.631 --> 43:55.424
But you had a responsibility
to be here--

43:55.591 --> 43:59.595
You both did. You were supposed to be
our parents and it is ridiculous...

43:59.762 --> 44:02.014
...that you've waited this long
to own up to it.

44:02.181 --> 44:04.350
I don't deny we could've handled things
a better way.

44:04.516 --> 44:06.935
You see,
at least someone is admitting it.

44:08.896 --> 44:10.189
Look.

44:11.023 --> 44:12.900
I'm sorry.

44:14.526 --> 44:17.404
And I will never forgive myself.

44:17.571 --> 44:19.698
[♪♪♪]

44:21.200 --> 44:23.494
But that doesn't mean
I want the whole world to know.

44:23.661 --> 44:27.748
If somebody had been here to explain,
I wouldn't have had to write about it.

44:27.915 --> 44:30.292
Everybody gets to know
everything we did right and wrong?

44:30.459 --> 44:33.212
BREE: Dad, I'm so sorry,
you are such a hypocrite.

44:33.379 --> 44:35.923
The truth only matters
if it doesn't include you?

44:36.090 --> 44:37.257
No, honey.

44:37.424 --> 44:40.219
The truth only matters
to the people in this room.

44:40.386 --> 44:41.720
Okay.

44:42.137 --> 44:43.847
Okay.

44:45.766 --> 44:47.184
[EXHALES]

45:01.865 --> 45:05.577
Once again,
the O'Brien family sits in silence.

45:17.089 --> 45:19.091
[♪♪♪] NARRATOR:
<i>Next time on </i>Chesapeake Shores:

45:50.664 --> 45:53.584
We'd like to buy you
a new bed and breakfast in Tanglewood.

45:53.750 --> 45:55.502
I applied to the Philadelphia F.D...

45:55.669 --> 45:57.671
-...as a paramedic.
-What are you gonna do?

45:57.838 --> 46:00.549
-He hasn't made his decision.
-Doesn't mean you can't make yours.

46:00.716 --> 46:03.260
Abby was the one who pushed you
to get back out. Are we a go?

46:03.427 --> 46:06.847
We can make this work.
We have before. We're doing it now.
